SECTION 9 — GOVERNING LAW AND DISPUTE RESOLUTION

9.1  GOVERNING LAW. This Agreement shall be governed by and construed in
     accordance with the laws of the Republic of Indonesia, without regard to
     its conflict-of-laws principles. The United Nations Convention on Contracts
     for the International Sale of Goods (CISG) shall not apply to this Agreement.

9.2  DISPUTE RESOLUTION. Any dispute, controversy, or claim arising out of or
     in connection with this Agreement, including any question regarding its
     existence, validity, breach, or termination, shall be resolved through the
     following sequential process:

     (a) INFORMAL NEGOTIATION. Either party may initiate informal negotiation
         by delivering written notice to the other party. The parties shall
         negotiate in good faith for a period of thirty (30) days following
         such notice ("Negotiation Period").

     (b) MEDIATION. If the dispute is not resolved during the Negotiation Period,
         either party may refer the dispute to non-binding mediation administered
         by the Indonesian Mediation Center (PMN — Pusat Mediasi Nasional) or
         a mutually agreed mediator, with costs shared equally.

     (c) ARBITRATION. If mediation fails to resolve the dispute within sixty
         (60) days of commencement, the dispute shall be submitted to final and
         binding arbitration before the Indonesian National Arbitration Board
         (BANI — Badan Arbitrase Nasional Indonesia), in accordance with BANI's
         Rules of Arbitration then in effect. The seat of arbitration shall be
         Jakarta, Indonesia. The arbitration shall be conducted in Bahasa
         Indonesia or English, at the election of the claimant. The decision of
         the arbitral tribunal shall be final and enforceable in any court of
         competent jurisdiction.

9.3  JURISDICTION. Notwithstanding Section 9.2, either party may seek interim
     or preliminary injunctive relief from any court of competent jurisdiction
     as necessary to protect its intellectual property rights or confidential
     information pending the resolution of a dispute.

